article.description:
Rashard Lewis atoned for his worst game of the
season with 30 points, leading the Seattle SuperSonics past the
Dallas Mavericks 107-100 Thursday night.
article.headline: Lewis scores 30 points as Seattle snaps skid
article.linkText: Aggressive Lewis takes out frustrations on Mavs
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Rashard Lewis is known as the Quiet Man, but his team's losing streak got him angry.
 
Lewis
So he took his frustrations out on the Dallas Mavericks, finishing with 30 points and 10 rebounds in leading the Seattle Supersonics to a 107-100 victory Thursday night. "I played with anger and aggression tonight," said Lewis, who made 12 of his 18 field goal attempts. "I've just been angry with how I've been playing and how we had lost three in a row." Lewis atoned for his season-low nine points in a loss to Portland on Tuesday. "He wants to be an integral part of the team," said Sonics head coach Nate McMillan, who game-planned Seattle's first five offensive sets to have the ball in Lewis' hands. "He's worked hard all season. He got lost for a few games with the new guys coming in, but tonight he was able to be aggressive." One of the new guys is Ray Allen, who had 29 points. Allen made 11 of his 18 shots from the floor, including a driving layup that he converted into a three-point play after he was fouled by Dirk Nowitzki. The free throw gave Seattle a 100-94 lead with 1:28 to play. Nowitzki scored 27 to lead the Mavericks, who still have the league's best record at 48-16. Dallas, coming off a home loss to Minnesota on Monday night, began a three-game West Coast trip. "The last couple of games we haven't been executing on offense," Nowitzki said. "Teams have been playing us very hard and have been ready with the best team rolling into town." Nick Van Exel added 26 points for the Mavs, and Steve Nash had 18. A free throw by Nowitzki with 58.2 seconds remaining cut the lead to 100-97, but the Mavericks' defense broke down on the next possession, and Lewis drove down the middle of the key for an uncontested dunk. "They were making all their shots down the stretch," said Nowitzki, who played 43 minutes and was victimized by Lewis on the clinching dunk. "I wasn't tired out there. We just didn't get the stops when we needed to." Mavericks coach Don Nelson thinks that Nowitzki probably was a little fatigued. "He played a lot of minutes, but he's got to buckle down and guard him," Nelson said. The Sonics shot 50 percent in the game. Lewis came out aggressive and was sharp with his shooting. He had 16 points in the first half on 7-for-9 shooting. "In the lockerroom before the game, we had the emphasis on Rashard being aggressive to start the game and really being involved," Allen said. "He's a guy who's still trying to figure out exactly what he can give to this offense." The game was tied at 78 to start the fourth quarter. Vladimir Radmanovic's fourth 3-pointer of the game gave Seattle a 93-87 lead with 4:28 to play. Van Exel then scored six straight points to tie it at 93 with 2:57 remaining. Dallas shot 49 percent, after shooting a season-worst 32 percent against the Timberwolves, but it wasn't enough. The two teams shot the ball well in the first quarter, when Nowitzki scored eight of his points and the game was tied six times. Seattle led 17-14 on a 3-pointer by Lewis with 3:18 to play in the period, but the Mavericks quickly responded with a four-point play when Nowitzki was fouled on a 3-pointer. Van Exel also hit a 3-pointer, giving the Mavs their biggest lead of the first half at 21-17. Lewis grabbed a missed 3-pointer by Brent Barry and slammed it down to give Seattle a 51-45 lead. The half came to an end when Michael Finley made a baseline 18-footer at the buzzer, cutting the Sonics' lead to 59-55. It was close the entire game, with 20 ties and 17 lead changes. Game notes
Dallas activated swingman Tariq Adbul-Wahad and placed guard Avery Johnson on the injured list with a strained right calf. Adbul-Wahad had missed the Mavericks' first 63 games with an injured left knee. ... Since opening the season at 31-5, the Mavericks are 17-11. ... Radmanovic is 8-of-14 from 3-point range over his last two games.
